  "title": "Internal Family Systems (IFS)",
  "evidenceStatus": "emerging",
  "category": "Approach",
  "blurb": "Befriend the different 'parts' of yourself.",
  "lead": "IFS sees the mind as made up of 'parts' — protectors, wounded parts, and a core Self. Healing comes from relating to these parts with curiosity and compassion.",
  "sections": [
    {
      "heading": "What it is",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "kind": "p",
          "text": "IFS, developed by Richard Schwartz, views the psyche as a system of 'parts', each with good intentions, centred around a calm, compassionate core Self."
        },
        {
          "kind": "p",
          "text": "Rather than fighting parts of yourself (like an inner critic), IFS helps you understand and heal them. Evidence is growing and promising, especially for trauma."
        }
      ]
    },
